The energy per unit surface which is necessary to create a sphere starting from a flat surface can be written as:6Gb=2κr2,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G_{{\text{b}}} = \frac{2\kappa }{{r^{2} }},$$\end{document}where κ is the membrane rigidity and r is the radius of the sphere. The rigidity κ can be expressed in terms of kBT, where kB is the Boltzmann constant and T is the absolute temperature. The energy cost for bending a membrane increases dramatically when formation of spheres of small radius (i.e. high curvature) is involved, such as those that occur during formation of the fusion stalk during viral infection. Modeling of this process suggests that minor increase in membrane rigidity, such as those caused by lipid oxidation produced in photosensitized production of 1O2 by lipophilic PSs, may impair the process [267, 269]. Damages to lipid bilayers are difficult to visualize in bacteria and viruses, but are more readily visualized on plasma membranes, where photo-oxidation induced by lipophilic PS leads to extensive damage that results in blebbing and membrane permeabilization. This is evident in Fig. 12 where close-up STED images on the plasma membrane portions of HeLa cells loaded with Hyp are shown [271].Fig. 12
Close-up images on swelling and vesicle formation as a consequence of the photoinduced damage on the plasma membrane on HeLa cells loaded with Hyp 0.5 μM during STED image collection (left and center). The plasma membrane swells toward the extracellular medium at those points marked by a white arrow. Spherical vesicles are detaching from the plasma membrane in the area surrounded by the dashed line (right). Scale bars, 10 μm. Figure adapted with permission from: P. Bianchini, M. Cozzolino, M. Oneto, L. Pesce, F. Pennacchietti, M. Tognolini, C. Giorgio, S. Nonell, L. Cavanna, P. Delcanale, S. Abbruzzetti, A. Diaspro, and C. Viappiani, Biomacromolecules, 20, 2024–2033 (2019).
